                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> I found the same thing early on. My friend in Rl has an Erudite Necro and they were telling me about fear kiting. I too found that the mobs would wander off, and even with taunt off, if they got too far out of range would just stay on the pet. Also by them wandering straight they tended to pick up a lot of adds. So I tanked untill high 20's if you can bieleve it. (Being and Iksar helped due to higher starting AC)<br /><br />Then I truly discovered fear kiting. Pathing depends on the zone you are in. Some zones the mob will fear in a straight path, and is generally a bitch. Others the feared mob will zig zag and is one of the most ideal pathing imo. The best is when they pace in one spot. Also in the high 20's your dots begin to get very strong and you will begin to outdamage your pet.<br /><br />The only way to figure out pathing honestly is to experiment. One good way is to snare, fear and then fd. Watching how the mob reacts and where it paths. THis of course requires you to /q or rot dot the mob once you are done. I usually did this in a zone I entered for the first time. It is just an area you have to experiment with, get to know the techniques and soon you will kite 90% of the time. However don't forget to practice root rotting. It is slower, but i still prefer to use this technique in many cases. Slower yes, but the trade of is greater controll, safety and the ability to kill multipule mobs.<br /><br />Krule Intentions<br />58 Iksar Heritic<br /><br /></span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
